# Task 4 — Measure SMC Round-trip Latency
## Green TEE | ARM TrustZone | Performance Analysis

---

## 1. What is This Task?

We wrote a Linux userspace program that measures how long one complete
SMC (Secure Monitor Call) round trip takes — from the moment a Normal
World application calls `ioctl()` to the moment it gets back the result
from the Secure World.

```
Start timer
    │
    ▼
NS-EL0 → NS-EL1 → EL3 → S-EL1 → EL3 → NS-EL1 → NS-EL0
    │
Stop timer
```

---

## 2. Why Did We Build This?

### 2.1 SMC is Not Free

Every time Linux talks to Green TEE, the CPU must:

```
1. Save all Linux registers (~30 system registers)
2. Switch world (SCR_EL3.NS = 0)
3. Restore Green TEE registers
4. Run Green TEE service
5. Save Green TEE registers
6. Switch world back (SCR_EL3.NS = 1)
7. Restore Linux registers
```

Each step has a cost. Without measuring, you don't know how expensive
TEE calls are.

### 2.2 Real World Importance

```
In real products:
  Android Keystore  → every fingerprint unlock = TEE call
  DRM               → every video frame decrypt = TEE call
  Secure Boot       → every signature verify = TEE call

If TEE call costs 5ms:
  Video at 60fps = 60 TEE calls/second
  60 × 5ms = 300ms just for TEE = system unusable

Engineers MUST know this cost before designing a system
```

### 2.3 Resume / Interview Importance

```
Shows you understand:
  → TrustZone is not just theory — it has real performance cost
  → World switch dominates cost, not the actual service
  → How to measure and quantify system behaviour
  → Engineering mindset: build, measure, analyse
```

