## 3. What Are We Measuring?

### 3.1 The Complete Journey of One SMC Call

```
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│  TIMER STARTS HERE                                          │
│                                                             │
│  NS-EL0: ioctl() called                                    │
│    │  SVC instruction → exception to NS-EL1                │
│    ▼                                                        │
│  NS-EL1: Linux TEE driver                                  │
│    copy_from_user()  → copy string from userspace          │
│    kzalloc()         → allocate kernel buffer              │
│    virt_to_phys()    → get physical address                │
│    │  SMC instruction → exception to EL3                   │
│    ▼                                                        │
│  EL3: TF-A green_teed SPD                                  │
│    cm_el1_sysregs_context_save(NON_SECURE)                 │
│      → saves: SCTLR_EL1, TTBR0_EL1, TTBR1_EL1,           │
│               TCR_EL1, MAIR_EL1, VBAR_EL1,                │
│               ELR_EL1, SPSR_EL1, SP_EL1 ...               │
│    cm_el1_sysregs_context_restore(SECURE)                  │
│      → restores Green TEE saved registers                  │
│    SCR_EL3.NS = 0    → switch to Secure World              │
│    ERET              → jump to Green TEE                   │
│    │                                                        │
│    ▼                                                        │
│  S-EL1: Green TEE                                          │
│    mmu_map_range()   → map NS buffer into S-EL1 tables     │
│    LOG("String: x")  → print to Secure UART               │
│    SMC(HANDLED)      → tell EL3 we are done               │
│    │                                                        │
│    ▼                                                        │
│  EL3: TF-A green_teed SPD                                  │
│    cm_el1_sysregs_context_save(SECURE)                     │
│      → saves Green TEE registers                           │
│    cm_el1_sysregs_context_restore(NON_SECURE)              │
│      → restores Linux registers                            │
│    SCR_EL3.NS = 1    → switch back to Normal World         │
│    ERET              → jump back to Linux                  │
│    │                                                        │
│    ▼                                                        │
│  NS-EL1: Linux driver returns                              │
│    ioctl() returns 0 to userspace                          │
│    │                                                        │
│    ▼                                                        │
│  NS-EL0: our program receives control back                 │
│                                                             │
│  TIMER STOPS HERE                                          │
└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
```

### 3.2 Two Services Measured

```
Service 1: GREEN_TEE_PRINT
  → sends 1 byte string to Secure World
  → minimal TEE processing
  → measures PURE world switch overhead

Service 2: GREEN_TEE_ENCRYPT
  → sends 4KB buffer to Secure World
  → TEE XOR-encrypts all 4096 bytes with OTP key
  → measures world switch + actual crypto cost

Difference = ENCRYPT - PRINT = actual encryption cost
```

