## 7. Results

### 7.1 PRINT Latency (World Switch Only)

```
Results:
  Average : 379,941 ns  (379 us)
  Minimum : 334,528 ns  (334 us)
  Maximum : 1,028,160 ns  (1028 us)
  Total   : 379,941,216 ns  (379 ms)
```

### 7.2 What Each Number Means

```
Average = 379 us
  → typical cost of one NS→S→NS world switch
  → this is what every ioctl to Green TEE costs
  → 1 second / 379 us = ~2638 TEE calls per second maximum

Minimum = 334 us
  → best case scenario
  → CPU cache warm, no interrupts, QEMU not busy
  → closest to "true" SMC cost

Maximum = 1028 us
  → worst case scenario
  → Linux timer interrupt fired during the call  OR
  → QEMU host machine was busy with other tasks  OR
  → CPU cache got evicted mid-way
  → 1028 / 334 = 3x variance — QEMU is not consistent

Spread (max - min) = 694 us
  → shows QEMU has high jitter
  → real hardware would show much tighter spread
  → typically 10-20% variance on real ARM
```

### 7.3 QEMU vs Real Hardware

```
Platform          World Switch Cost    Notes
─────────────────────────────────────────────────────
QEMU (measured)   379 us               Software emulation
Cortex-A55        ~2-5 us              Real silicon
Cortex-A78        ~1-3 us              Real silicon
Cortex-A510       ~2-4 us              Real silicon

QEMU overhead = 379 / 3 = ~126x slower

Why QEMU is slow:
  → QEMU translates ARM64 instructions to x86 in software
  → Each ARM instruction = multiple x86 instructions
  → 30 register saves × 126x = very slow
  → Real chip does context switch in silicon = nanoseconds
```

