## 10. Key Concepts Demonstrated

### 10.1 CLOCK_MONOTONIC vs CLOCK_REALTIME

```
CLOCK_REALTIME:
  → wall clock time
  → can jump forward or backward (NTP adjustments)
  → NOT suitable for measuring intervals

CLOCK_MONOTONIC:
  → always increases
  → never jumps
  → perfect for measuring elapsed time
  → what we used ✅
```

### 10.2 Why Physical Address Matters for Latency

```
Linux driver does virt_to_phys() before SMC:
  → converts kernel virtual address to physical
  → adds small overhead (~50ns)

Without this:
  → Green TEE cannot access the buffer
  → Green TEE has different page tables
  → VA in Linux is meaningless in S-EL1

This address translation is included in our measurement
```

### 10.3 The mmu_map_range Cost

```
Inside Green TEE, before reading NS buffer:
  mmu_map_range(x1, x1, x1+PAGE_SIZE, PT_SECURE|...);

This:
  → walks 3-level page table (L1→L2→L3)
  → allocates new page table entries
  → writes physical address + flags
  → adds latency to every call

This cost is included in our PRINT measurement.
Could be optimised by pre-mapping NS shared memory at boot.
```

